<Base title="About — Simon Plant" description="Chief architect turned fractional CTO — 30+ years designing and delivering enterprise systems, from early AWS to AI in production." jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <main class="section-spacing">
    <div class="prose">
      <h1>About</h1>

      <p>
        I've spent thirty years as the chief architect for whatever is new — infrastructure services on one side, customer and company solutions on the other. Web hosting in 1994. Enterprise cloud in 2008. DevOps in 2014. AI now. The pattern is always the same: a powerful new platform shows up, everyone builds demos, and someone has to design the system — and the delivery plan — that makes it real. That's usually been me.
      </p>

      <p>
        As I've gotten more senior, the seat has evolved into CTO roles. What hasn't changed: I still write code — more than ever now that I build solo — and I still spend the other half of the week advising leadership and program teams.
      </p>

      <h2>The short version</h2>

      <p>
        I'm a Fractional CTO based in Los Angeles. I work with 2–3 companies at a time on AI strategy, enterprise architecture, and the technology decisions that determine whether you scale or stall. I also design, build, and run my own AI systems in production. CISSP. Originally from the UK.
      </p>

      <h2>The long version</h2>

      <p>
        I started at IBM in 1994 building one of the UK's first commercial web hosting platforms. Moved to Capgemini and spent seven years as a Chief Enterprise Architect — first on major UK retail accounts (Tesco, Marks &amp; Spencer), then on General Motors' $2 billion IT in-sourcing program in Detroit, where I managed a team of 50 enterprise architects. In 2008 I introduced AWS to GM and trained over 100 of their architects on cloud. That led to building Capgemini's cloud practice from scratch and making them the first Systems Integrator to partner with AWS — a milestone their CEO acknowledged publicly.
      </p>

      <p>
        RightScale recruited me to run their professional services. We became AWS's largest consulting partner, which caught Amazon's attention — they recruited me to build their Western US Professional Services organization from scratch. I built a team of 80+, served clients including Adobe, Apple, Boeing, and Intuit, and delivered AWS's first million-dollar consulting engagement.
      </p>

      <p>
        In 2014 I co-founded DualSpark, a DevOps consultancy. We scaled to 35 engineers in nine months, ran transformations for Nike, Experian, FICO, 23andMe, and VSCO, and exited to Datapipe in fourteen months.
      </p>

      <p>
        After that: founded Mode2 as an AWS Advanced partner building serverless and cloud-native systems, led technology enablement at Slalom in LA working with Riot Games, UCLA, USC, Amazon Studios, and PennyMac, ran a $100M professional services organization at Rackspace with 540 engineers across the Americas, and served as CTO at Redapt across AWS, Generative AI, and security platforms.
      </p>

      <p>
        Now I run my Fractional CTO practice through Mode2 — my own company, and these days a deliberately solo vehicle. The throughline across all of it: architect first — design the system, write the delivery plan, stay through delivery — then help companies adopt what's new without the expensive mistakes.
      </p>

      <h2>What I do for clients</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>AI reality checks.</strong> Cutting through the hype to find where AI actually moves the needle — and protecting data privacy and IP while you do it.</li>
        <li><strong>Architecture strategy.</strong> Spotting the "small" decisions that become "large" technical debt. I've watched this movie enough times to recognize the pattern early.</li>
        <li><strong>Executive advisory.</strong> Build-vs-buy, vendor selection, team structure — the decisions where thirty years of context on what works and what doesn't is worth more than another meeting.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        I can code-review a Python data application in the morning and present AI strategy to your Board in the afternoon. That's the bridge I build. More on the <a href="/services">services page</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What I'm building</h2>

      <p>When I'm not working with clients, I build and run my own AI systems in production:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><a href="/projects/sterling"><strong>Sterling</strong></a> — a sovereign, local-first advisory trading agent. Proposes, briefs, and alerts; never places an order.</li>
        <li><a href="/projects/markdown"><strong>Markdown</strong></a> — a free, open-source markdown editor for iOS.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Earlier experiments — <a href="/projects/clawhq">ClawHQ</a> and <a href="/projects/aishore">AIShore</a> — are retired but documented on the <a href="/projects">projects page</a>, because the journey is part of the record.
      </p>

      <h2>Get in touch</h2>

      <p>
        If you're working through a technology decision where the cost of getting it wrong is high — AI adoption, architecture strategy, build-vs-buy, team structure — that's the conversation I want to have.
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="mailto:website@simonplant.com">website@simonplant.com</a> &middot;
        <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/simonplant" rel="me">LinkedIn</a>
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Colophon</h2>

      <p>
        This site is built with <a href="https://astro.build">Astro</a> and <a href="https://tailwindcss.com">Tailwind CSS</a>. No JavaScript frameworks — every page is static HTML and CSS. Typography is Literata for prose, DM Serif Display for headings, JetBrains Mono for code. Dark mode only.
      </p>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
